  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="ITA82">
<l>vaṭikkōla vāṇeṭuṅkaṇ māmalarāḷ cevvip</l>
<l>paṭikkōlaṅ kaṇṭakalāḷ paṉṉā – ḷaṭikkōli</l>
<l>ñālattāḷ piṉṉu nalampurinta teṉkolō</l>
<l>kōlattā lillai kuṟai</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>The Lady in the big blossom with shapely beautiful bright large eyes<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Or: “with large sword eyes of the beauty of green mangoes”. Sword or spear eyes – eyes that are like weapons attacking men – are a standard trope in classical Tamil poetry. For the slightly rarer comparison of eyes that have the oval form of cut green mango, cf. NA 133.1f. kaṇṇē | vāḷ īr vaṭiyiṉ vaṭiv’ iḻantaṉavē, “the eyes, they have lost the beautiful shape of green mangoes cut by a sword”.</note>, seeing</l>
<l>the beauty of [his] graceful body, she did not leave for many days. Even after,</l>
<l>why would Earth<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">ñālattāḷ, lit. “she of the earth”, that is, the female deity.</note> make preparations [and] desire [his] beauty?</l>
<l>There is no lack of beauty.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
